283#define XN_FLAG_SEP_MASK (0xf << 16)
284
285#define XN_FLAG_COMPAT 0 // Traditional SSLeay: use old X509_NAME_print
286#define XN_FLAG_SEP_COMMA_PLUS (1 << 16) // RFC2253 ,+
287#define XN_FLAG_SEP_CPLUS_SPC (2 << 16) // ,+ spaced: more readable
288#define XN_FLAG_SEP_SPLUS_SPC (3 << 16) // ;+ spaced
289#define XN_FLAG_SEP_MULTILINE (4 << 16) // One line per field
290
291#define XN_FLAG_DN_REV (1 << 20) // Reverse DN order
292
293// How the field name is shown
294
295#define XN_FLAG_FN_MASK (0x3 << 21)
296
297#define XN_FLAG_FN_SN 0 // Object short name
298#define XN_FLAG_FN_LN (1 << 21) // Object long name
299#define XN_FLAG_FN_OID (2 << 21) // Always use OIDs
300#define XN_FLAG_FN_NONE (3 << 21) // No field names
301
302#define XN_FLAG_SPC_EQ (1 << 23) // Put spaces round '='
303
304// This determines if we dump fields we don't recognise:
305// RFC2253 requires this.
306
307#define XN_FLAG_DUMP_UNKNOWN_FIELDS (1 << 24)
308
309#define XN_FLAG_FN_ALIGN (1 << 25) // Align field names to 20 characters
310
311// Complete set of RFC2253 flags
312
313#define XN_FLAG_RFC2253 \
314 (ASN1_STRFLGS_RFC2253 | XN_FLAG_SEP_COMMA_PLUS | XN_FLAG_DN_REV | \
315 XN_FLAG_FN_SN | XN_FLAG_DUMP_UNKNOWN_FIELDS)
316
317// readable oneline form
318
319#define XN_FLAG_ONELINE \
320 (ASN1_STRFLGS_RFC2253 | ASN1_STRFLGS_ESC_QUOTE | XN_FLAG_SEP_CPLUS_SPC | \
321 XN_FLAG_SPC_EQ | XN_FLAG_FN_SN)
322
323// readable multiline form
324
325#define XN_FLAG_MULTILINE \
326 (ASN1_STRFLGS_ESC_CTRL | ASN1_STRFLGS_ESC_MSB | XN_FLAG_SEP_MULTILINE | \
327 XN_FLAG_SPC_EQ | XN_FLAG_FN_LN | XN_FLAG_FN_ALIGN)

443// X509_VERSION_* are X.509 version numbers. Note the numerical values of all
444// defined X.509 versions are one less than the named version.
445#define X509_VERSION_1 0
446#define X509_VERSION_2 1
447#define X509_VERSION_3 2

449// X509_get_version returns the numerical value of |x509|'s version. Callers may
450// compare the result to the |X509_VERSION_*| constants. Unknown versions are
451// rejected by the parser, but a manually-created |X509| object may encode
452// invalid versions. In that case, the function will return the invalid version,
453// or -1 on overflow.
454OPENSSL_EXPORT long X509_get_version(const X509 *x509);
455
456// X509_set_version sets |x509|'s version to |version|, which should be one of
457// the |X509V_VERSION_*| constants. It returns one on success and zero on error.
458//
459// If unsure, use |X509_VERSION_3|.
460OPENSSL_EXPORT int X509_set_version(X509 *x509, long version);

508// X509_get0_uids sets |*out_issuer_uid| to a non-owning pointer to the
509// issuerUID field of |x509|, or NULL if |x509| has no issuerUID. It similarly
510// outputs |x509|'s subjectUID field to |*out_subject_uid|.
511//
512// Callers may pass NULL to either |out_issuer_uid| or |out_subject_uid| to
513// ignore the corresponding field.

522// X509_get_pathlen returns path length constraint from the basic constraints
523// extension in |x509|. (See RFC5280, section 4.2.1.9.) It returns -1 if the
524// constraint is not present, or if some extension in |x509| was invalid.
525//
526// Note that decoding an |X509| object will not check for invalid extensions. To
527// detect the error case, call |X509_get_extensions_flags| and check the
528// |EXFLAG_INVALID| bit.
529OPENSSL_EXPORT long X509_get_pathlen(X509 *x509);

871// X509_ALGOR_set0 sets |alg| to an AlgorithmIdentifier with algorithm |obj| and
872// parameter determined by |param_type| and |param_value|. It returns one on
873// success and zero on error. This function takes ownership of |obj| and
874// |param_value| on success.
875//
876// If |param_type| is |V_ASN1_UNDEF|, the parameter is omitted. If |param_type|
877// is zero, the parameter is left unchanged. Otherwise, |param_type| and
878// |param_value| are interpreted as in |ASN1_TYPE_set|.
879//
880// Note omitting the parameter (|V_ASN1_UNDEF|) and encoding an explicit NULL
881// value (|V_ASN1_NULL|) are different. Some algorithms require one and some the
882// other. Consult the relevant specification before calling this function. The
883// correct parameter for an RSASSA-PKCS1-v1_5 signature is |V_ASN1_NULL|. The
884// correct one for an ECDSA or Ed25519 signature is |V_ASN1_UNDEF|.
885OPENSSL_EXPORT int X509_ALGOR_set0(X509_ALGOR *alg, ASN1_OBJECT *obj,
886 int param_type, void *param_value);
887
888// X509_ALGOR_get0 sets |*out_obj| to the |alg|'s algorithm. If |alg|'s
889// parameter is omitted, it sets |*out_param_type| and |*out_param_value| to
890// |V_ASN1_UNDEF| and NULL. Otherwise, it sets |*out_param_type| and
891// |*out_param_value| to the parameter, using the same representation as
892// |ASN1_TYPE_set0|. See |ASN1_TYPE_set0| and |ASN1_TYPE| for details.
893//
894// Callers that require the parameter in serialized form should, after checking
895// for |V_ASN1_UNDEF|, use |ASN1_TYPE_set1| and |d2i_ASN1_TYPE|, rather than
896// inspecting |*out_param_value|.
897//
898// Each of |out_obj|, |out_param_type|, and |out_param_value| may be NULL to
899// ignore the output. If |out_param_type| is NULL, |out_param_value| is ignored.
900//
901// WARNING: If |*out_param_type| is set to |V_ASN1_UNDEF|, OpenSSL and older
902// revisions of BoringSSL leave |*out_param_value| unset rather than setting it
903// to NULL. Callers that support both OpenSSL and BoringSSL should not assume
904// |*out_param_value| is uniformly initialized.
905OPENSSL_EXPORT void X509_ALGOR_get0(const ASN1_OBJECT **out_obj,
906 int *out_param_type,
907 const void **out_param_value,
908 const X509_ALGOR *alg);

1683// X509_ATTRIBUTE_set1_data appends a value to |attr|'s value set and returns
1684// one on success or zero on error. The value is determined as follows:
1685//
1686// If |attrtype| is a |MBSTRING_*| constant, the value is an ASN.1 string. The
1687// string is determined by decoding |len| bytes from |data| in the encoding
1688// specified by |attrtype|, and then re-encoding it in a form appropriate for
1689// |attr|'s type. If |len| is -1, |strlen(data)| is used instead. See
1690// |ASN1_STRING_set_by_NID| for details.
1691//
1692// TODO(davidben): Document |ASN1_STRING_set_by_NID| so the reference is useful.
1693//
1694// Otherwise, if |len| is not -1, the value is an ASN.1 string. |attrtype| is an
1695// |ASN1_STRING| type value and the |len| bytes from |data| are copied as the
1696// type-specific representation of |ASN1_STRING|. See |ASN1_STRING| for details.
1697//
1698// WARNING: If this form is used to construct a negative INTEGER or ENUMERATED,
1699// |attrtype| includes the |V_ASN1_NEG| flag for |ASN1_STRING|, but the function
1700// forgets to clear the flag for |ASN1_TYPE|. This matches OpenSSL but is
1701// probably a bug. For now, do not use this form with negative values.
1702//
1703// Otherwise, if |len| is -1, the value is constructed by passing |attrtype| and
1704// |data| to |ASN1_TYPE_set1|. That is, |attrtype| is an |ASN1_TYPE| type value,
1705// and |data| is cast to the corresponding pointer type.
1706//
1707// WARNING: Despite the name, this function appends to |attr|'s value set,
1708// rather than overwriting it. To overwrite the value set, create a new
1709// |X509_ATTRIBUTE| with |X509_ATTRIBUTE_new|.
1710//
1711// WARNING: If using the |MBSTRING_*| form, pass a length rather than relying on
1712// |strlen|. In particular, |strlen| will not behave correctly if the input is
1713// |MBSTRING_BMP| or |MBSTRING_UNIV|.
1714//
1715// WARNING: This function currently misinterprets |V_ASN1_OTHER| as an
1716// |MBSTRING_*| constant. This matches OpenSSL but means it is impossible to
1717// construct a value with a non-universal tag.
1718OPENSSL_EXPORT int X509_ATTRIBUTE_set1_data(X509_ATTRIBUTE *attr, int attrtype,
1719 const void *data, int len);

1774// X509_PUBKEY_get0_param outputs fields of |pub| and returns one. If |out_obj|
1775// is not NULL, it sets |*out_obj| to AlgorithmIdentifier's OID. If |out_key|
1776// is not NULL, it sets |*out_key| and |*out_key_len| to the encoded public key.
1777// If |out_alg| is not NULL, it sets |*out_alg| to the AlgorithmIdentifier.
1778//
